      DependencyGraph DependencyGraph.normalizeActivePassive(DependencyGraph graph)
      normalize dependency relations for passive forms: swap dependency relations for subj and obja/objp-von/objp-vom Example: "Der Kuchen wurde von Jan geliebt" - "der Kuchen" must be target and therefore changed to an obja-relation (although it is the sentence's subject) "von Jan" is source and its dependency relation must change from objp-von to subj

      java.lang.Object ConstituencyTree.getArgumentNode(WordObj predicate, WordObj argument, DependencyGraph depGraph)
      Given an argument and a predicate in a ConstituencyTree, we want to return a node which a) either dominates the argument node or is the argument node b) is directly dominated by the node which dominates both the predicate and the argument node Example: [ S [ NP [ DET The] [ N gardener] [ VP [V likes ] [ NP [ PN his ] [ N flowers ] ] ] ] ] Given that "likes" is the predicate and "gardener" is the argument, this function will first find the lowest node in the tree which dominates both the predicate and argument node (here: S: "The gardener likes his flowers").
